defaultThe Russian Trading Structure
default&#xa0;
default16. 
defaultENRC is a company with Kazakh origins 
defaultthat 
defaultis largely controlled by its trio of founding shareholders: Patokh Chodiev, Alijan Ibragimov and Alexander Mashkevitch.
default&#xa0;
default17. 
defaultGlobal Witness has investigated
default corruption concerns around the company’s business in the DRC and has also reviewed audits which, among other matters, show how the trio siphoned money out of its Kazakh factories. The evidence not only demonstrates the importance of the UK
default authorities pur
defaultsuing their current
default investigations into ENRC to their conclusion but also raises serious regulatory questions for the Stock Exchange authorities – including 
defaultwhy
default ENRC 
defaultwas allowed 
defaultto list in the first place. 
default&#xa0;
default18. 
defaultTo comply with the word limit here, we focus
default on the most damning of these audits. We would be glad to offer supplementary material, oral or written
default.
default&#xa0;
default19.
default 
defaultA September 2007 audit by the law firm Herbert Smith explains how the trio skimmed most of the profits from mineral sales to Russia in the years p
defaultreceding ENRC’s London listing in December 2007. The audit examined how, from 2004 to 2006, four factories in Kazakhstan sold $870 million of coal, iron ore and other minerals to Russia through layers of anonymously owned intermediary companies, collective
defaultly referred to
default in the audit
default as the Russian Trading Structure (RTS). 
default&#xa0;
default20.
default 
defaultThe factories concerned – majority-owned by the trio – were incorporated as separate entities from 2004 but were grouped under the ENRC umbrella in December 2006. Seventy per cent of
default all profits went personally to the three founder shareholders in cash, the 
defaultaudit
default said.
default&#xa0;
default21.
default 
defaultThe RTS was “based on entirely illegitimate objectives”, wrote Pieter Hamelink, a Dutch tax lawyer who headed ENRC’s Audit Committee, in a 6 April 2006 e-mail cite
defaultd by the auditors. 
defaultThe audit said that 
defaultENRC’s smaller shareholders could have been “prejudiced by the transfer of profits away from the plants”.
default&#xa0;
default22.
default 
default“The plants received, via bank transfer, a payment for their products,” said the audit. “This did not represent the total amount of payment as the RTS would also pay a cash element in respect of each transaction… for the benefit of Messers Chodiev, Ibragim
defaultov and Machkevitch.” 
default&#xa0;
default23.
default 
defaultPatokh Chodiev’s nephew, Olim, was the trio’s “treasur
defaulter” tasked with collecting the
default cash, 
defaultaccording to the audit
default: “Olim Chodiev told us that he did not see any documentation in relation to the RTS arrangement and would simply co
defaultllect the money.”
default&#xa0;
default24. 
defaultWhile two senior officials told Herbert Smith that the RTS structure was independent of the trio, the 
defaultaudit
default provides substantial evidence that this was untrue. For example, one key firm in the RTS, Ugolenergoimpex, was “ultimately, b
defaulteneficially owned by the Majority Shareholders [the trio]”, according to the head of the Moscow branch of ENRC Marketing, Anatoliy Tulyakov. Mr Tulyakov was a director of Ugolenergoimpex and was thus in a position to know about its ownership.  Evidence in 
defaultthe audit from 
defaultMr Hamelink
default and from ENRC’s Swiss tax advisers also indicate that the trio beneficially owned companies in the RTS.
default&#xa0;
default25.
default 
defaultAs well as skimming
default profits, RTS companies also took 
defaultextra commission
defaults
default. If the
default trio
default were the beneficial owners of the RTS companies, the
defaultir
default cut of the profits may have been above 70%.
default 
default&#xa0;
default26. 
defaultFrom reading the 
defaultaudit
default, it 
defaultappears to Global Witness that
default th
defaulte RTS
default arrangement could have been fraudulent, with the trio siphoning off profits from ENR
defaultC in cash through anonymously owned companies 
defaultto
default the expense of ENRC’s other shareholders.
default 
default&#xa0;
default27.
default 
defaultMuch potential evidence has vanished. Key ENRC officials in Moscow had “not provided us with an honest account” when questioned about deleting data about the R
defaultTS, while other officials refused to answer questions, Herbert Smith wrote. Prior to the Herbert Smith analysis, PwC was sent falsified information as 
defaultit
default sought to audit company revenues. During a later investigation, the UK law firm Dechert wrote in a let
defaultter to ENRC of 12 April 2013 that a false office was even created in Kazakhstan. 
default&#xa0;
default28.
default 
defaultIt was not until the end of 2006 that the RTS system was closed down. In 2006, sales from ENRC’s Kazakhstan plants to Russia involved UK-registered Tekmark Consulting Lt
defaultd 
default, which the auditors “
defaultunderstand is a company put forward by the RTS”. Tekmark signed “commission agreements” with ENRC subsidiaries, formally giving it a role in selling metal to Russia.
default&#xa0;
default29.
default 
defaultThe agreements with Tekmark appear to have made no fundamental difference to the RTS structure, with Herbert Smith saying “we understand that during 2006 the Majority Shareholders continued to receive the cash from the RTS in Moscow”.
default&#xa0;
default30.
default 
defaultTekmark
default appears 
defaultto been have no more than a shell: “Given that Tekmark is recorded as being a dormant company at the time when the services are being provided with assets of £300 it seems unlikely, in practice, to have provided any services whatsoever,” the audit said. 
default&#xa0;
default31.
default 
defaultThe people who own Tekmark are unknown, as documents filed at UK Companies House show its sole shareholder as a being another anonymously-owned company: Vestro Development, registered in Gibraltar.
default&#xa0;
default32.
default 
defaultDespite the extremely serious findings of the aud
defaultit, ENRC 
defaultwas able to
default go ahead and list o
defaultn the London Stock Exchange less than three months
default after it was submitted. Membership of the FTSE100 ensured that UK pensioners would automatically buy its stock through tracker funds. 
default&#xa0;
default33.
default 
defaultENRC’s
default Initial Public Off
defaultering (IPO) prospectus declared the RTS as a “risk factor” and recognised that it paid out $111 million to the trio. Yet the details the IPO provided of the RTS are contradicted by Herbert Smith. ENRC professed general ignorance about 
defaulthow the RTS was struc
defaulttured and about 
defaultthe “agency” organising
default it (ENRC said it believes th
defaultis
default 
default“
defaultagency
default…
defaultwas neither owned or legally controlled by the Group or its shareholders
default”)
default. However, the audit cites Johannes Sittard, then the CEO of ENRC, saying that every three to six month
defaults “there would be a special presentation made… concerning money which had been earned by the Majority Shareholders from RTS sales. This presentation would be restricted to the Majority Shareholders and Dr Sittard… During these presentations Ilmir Masgutov 
default[a consultant to the factories] would hand out documentation which set out the results of the RTS trading.”  The audit shows that several officials working for the trio and its companies had a detailed knowledge of the RTS.
