defaultFor over a year now
default Global Witness 
defaulthas been 
defaultpiec
defaulting 
defaulttogether detailed court documents and other evidence that expose how 
defaultShell and Italian oil giant
default Eni agreed to pay US$1.092
default billion for one of Nigeria’s most potentially lucrative oil blocks, OPL245. 
default&#xa0;
default44. 
defaultThe payment was made by Shell and Eni
default to the Nigerian government, which
default had a separate agreement to pay the same amount to Malabu Oil and Gas, a 
defaultN
defaultigerian 
defaultcompany widely believed at the time to be controlled by convicted money-launderer and former Nigerian oil minister Dan Etete.
default&#xa0;
default45. 
defaultIn July 2013, a British High Court court ruled that Etete was indeed the owner of Malabu. As Etete had awarded the oi
defaultl block to Malabu whilst 
defaultpetroleum
default minister during the regime of the corrupt dictator General Abacha, he had effectively given himself one of the most lucrative oil blocks in Nigeria.
default&#xa0;
default46. 
defaultShell and Eni deny paying any money to Malabu. However, High Court 
defaultproceedings and other evidence seen by Global Witness reveal that in reality Shell and Eni were aware an
defaultd in agreement that the deal would
default benefit Malabu, and had even met with 
defaultEtete face-to-face on several occasions. In fact, testimony heard during the ca
defaultse indicates that an official from Shell previously negotiated directly with Etete over “iced champagne” and that Eni officials had enjoyed a luxurious dinner at a 5-
defaults
defaulttar 
defaulth
defaultotel in Milan with Etete.  
default&#xa0;
default47. 
defaultGlobal Witness believes that the deal was structure
defaultd 
defaultthrough the Nigerian government
default primarily to allo
defaultw Shell and Eni to claim that they
default had not struck a deal with Etete or Malabu. Yet in making these payments, Shell and Eni had effectively bought the block from Etete for over a billion dollars, there
defaultby
default “m
defaultonetising” an asset that was originally acquired by Malabu
default in highly suspicious and proba
defaultbly illegal circumstances.   
default&#xa0;
default48. 
defaultDocuments seen by Global Witness also indicate that the deal resulted in over $801 million of the m
defaultoney transferred to Malabu
default being 
defaultpassed on 
defaultto five 
defaultNigerian 
defaultshell companies with
