default54. defaultThe UK is the leading centre for private dispute resolution. It should use its position to defaultmakedefault arbitration proceedingsdefault transparentdefault in cases where there is a significant public interest, such as OPL245. defaultAbove all, courts should not decide arbitration proceedings prior to determining whether the funds in question could be the proceeds of crime – otherwise they risk defaultfacilitatingdefault state ldefaultooting. defaultCitizens shodefaultuld not be kept in ignorance of ddefaultecisions which have serious implications for them.  Details of such proceedings should be made public and their outcomes should be published. default&#xa0;
default55. 
defaultThe cases discussed above amply illustrate the huge cor
defaultruption concerns surrounding extractives companies listed and registered in the UK
default, and the damage this is doing to the UK’s reputation for probity. Opacity around resource deals and company ownership is a central part of the problem. For matters to improv
defaulte the UK will have to introduce new laws and take firmer action against corporate misbehaviour. To start with, the UK should follow through on its promises, putting in place a public register of beneficial ownership and transposing the EU Transparency and 
defaultAccounting Directive into UK law. 
